I am choosing to elect the “best” neighborhood in Pittsburgh by the following criteria:

-Housing Values

-Owner Occupancy

-Residential Vacancy

-Parks/“Green Space” 

-Proximity to City of Pittsburgh 
    
I think these criteria constitute as the “best” for a few reasons. First, housing values reflect the wealth of an area. When a neighborhood, city, or suburb is wealthier, it is often kept cleaner and has nicer infrastructure (such as better bridges or paved roads). Second, owner occupancy is an important factor when it comes to the permanence of the neighborhood. For example, if more homes are bought instead of rented, the neighborhood is subject to less change since there aren’t many people moving in and out of the area. Third, I think that parks are important to neighborhoods because it reflects that the environment is being respected. When forests and nature are preserved, it not only saves the environment but saves the beauty of nature as well. Fourth, I am considering each neighborhood’s proximity to the city of Pittsburgh for convenience and travel purposes. 


![image.png](attachment:2371e5f4-d31c-449f-a3c6-5ef1d40a0463.png)


There are four different types of housing markets: robust, steady, transitional, and distressed. 

Robust Markets

“A” markets have the highest housing values, experience the largest level of new construction, have the highest owner occupancy levels, and experience little housing distress (such as residential vacancy and foreclosure).

“B” markets have elevated housing values, experience substantial amounts of new construction, have high levels of owner occupancy, and experience little housing distress.

Steady Markets

“C” markets have above average housing values, about average levels of new construction, have high levels of owner occupancy, and experience little housing distress. 

“D” markets have slightly below average housing values, experience half the countywide average amount of new construction, have more renters than owners, and experience about average levels of foreclosure and residential vacancy. 

“E” markets have slightly lower than average housing values, experience half the countywide average amount of new construction, have high levels of owner occupancy, have low levels of residential vacancy but about average levels of foreclosure.

Transitional Markets 

“F” markets have housing values about half the countywide average, experience little new construction, have more owners than renters, and experience about average levels of foreclosure and residential vacancy. 

“G” markets have below average housing values, experience little new construction, have slightly more owners than renters, and experience about twice the countywide average levels of foreclosure and residential vacancy.

Distressed Markets 

“H” markets have housing values well below the countywide average, experience little new construction, have more renters than owners, experience elevated levels of residential vacancy and the highest levels of foreclosure in the County. 

“I” markets have the lowest housing values in Allegheny County, experience little new construction, have about an even share of owners and renters, experience the highest levels of residential vacancy and elevated levels of foreclosure.
![image.png](attachment:3088512f-6991-489a-ac6e-c6c6fc3cf2c6.png)

From this data, it can be concluded that the “A” cluster reflects the best neighborhoods house-market-wise, and cluster “B” comes in close second. 
![image.png](attachment:01c5bafa-6061-42bc-b919-2effb2419985.png)

![image.png](attachment:d6e53cc8-1909-4174-acf5-cf2868f3c274.png)



Looking at this, we can see that the areas that have the highest median sales price are the same areas that are in cluster "A", so we must look further into green space and proximity to the city. 

![image.png](attachment:e6f1f480-8f17-4339-af7a-607ab8cf9ac1.png)

Looking at the park to neighborhood ratio, Fox Chapel has the highest based on the diagram. It is also the closest cluster "A" neighborhood to the city of Pittsburgh.

Therefore, Fox Chapel is the best neighborhood in Pittsburgh because it fits into cluster "A" (which has the highest housing values, experience the largest level of new construction, have the highest owner occupancy levels, and experience little housing distress), has the largest park-to-neighborhood ratio, and is the closest to the city. Personally, Fox Chapel is my favorite neighborhood purely because of the scenery. I like the neighborhood for all of the same reasons the data reflects: the beautiful houses, scenery, and proximity to the city.
